{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":206955,"duration_api_ms":206942,"num_turns":1,"result":"# Comprehensive Guide to Sorting Algorithms\n\n---\n\n## Table of Contents\n1. [Bubble Sort](#1-bubble-sort)\n2. [Selection Sort](#2-selection-sort)\n3. [Insertion Sort](#3-insertion-sort)\n4. [Merge Sort](#4-merge-sort)\n5. [Quick Sort](#5-quick-sort)\n6. [Heap Sort](#6-heap-sort)\n7. [Counting Sort](#7-counting-sort)\n8. [Radix Sort](#8-radix-sort)\n9. [Comparison Summary](#9-comparison-summary)\n\n---\n\n## 1. Bubble Sort\n\n### Algorithm Description\n\nBubble Sort repeatedly steps through the list, compares adjacent elements, and swaps them if they are in the wrong order. Each full pass \"bubbles\" the largest unsorted element to its correct position at the end. The process repeats until no swaps are needed.\n\n**Steps:**\n1. Start at index 0. Compare `arr[0]` and `arr[1]`.\n2. If `arr[0] > arr[1]`, swap them.\n3. Move to index 1. Compare `arr[1]` and `arr[2]`. Swap if needed.\n4. Continue until the end of the array. The last element is now in its correct position.\n5. Repeat for the remaining unsorted portion (shrink the boundary by 1 each pass).\n6. Stop when a full pass completes with zero swaps (array is sorted).\n\n### Complexity Analysis\n\n| Case | Time | Why |\n|------|------|-----|\n| Best | O(n) | Already sorted — one pass, no swaps, early exit |\n| Average | O(n²) | ~n²/2 comparisons on average |\n| Worst | O(n²) | Reverse-sorted — every pair swaps on every pass |\n| **Space** | **O(1)** | In-place; only a temp variable for swapping |\n\n**Key insight:** After pass `k`, the last `k` elements are guaranteed to be in their final positions. Each pass does `n - k - 1` comparisons.\n\n### Python Implementation\n\n```python\ndef bubble_sort(arr):\n    n = len(arr)\n    \n    for i in range(n):\n        # After pass i, the last i elements are already sorted.\n        # swapped tracks whether any swap occurred in this pass.\n        swapped = False\n        \n        # Inner loop only needs to go up to n-i-1 because\n        # the last i elements are already in their final positions.\n        for j in range(0, n - i - 1):\n            \n            # Compare adjacent elements\n            if arr[j] > arr[j + 1]:\n                # Swap using Python's tuple unpacking (no temp variable needed)\n                arr[j], arr[j + 1] = arr[j + 1], arr[j]\n                swapped = True\n        \n        # Optimization: if no swap occurred in this pass,\n        # the array is already sorted — stop early.\n        if not swapped:\n            break\n    \n    return arr\n```\n\n### Example Trace: `[64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]`\n\n```\nInitial:  [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]\n\n--- Pass 1 (i=0): bubble largest to end ---\n  j=0: compare 64,34 → swap → [34, 64, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]\n  j=1: compare 64,25 → swap → [34, 25, 64, 12, 22, 11, 90]\n  j=2: compare 64,12 → swap → [34, 25, 12, 64, 22, 11, 90]\n  j=3: compare 64,22 → swap → [34, 25, 12, 22, 64, 11, 90]\n  j=4: compare 64,11 → swap → [34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 64, 90]\n  j=5: compare 64,90 → ok   → [34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 64, 90]\n  End of pass: 90 is in final position ✓\n\n--- Pass 2 (i=1): bubble 2nd largest ---\n  j=0: compare 34,25 → swap → [25, 34, 12, 22, 11, 64, 90]\n  j=1: compare 34,12 → swap → [25, 12, 34, 22, 11, 64, 90]\n  j=2: compare 34,22 → swap → [25, 12, 22, 34, 11, 64, 90]\n  j=3: compare 34,11 → swap → [25, 12, 22, 11, 34, 64, 90]\n  j=4: compare 34,64 → ok   → [25, 12, 22, 11, 34, 64, 90]\n  End of pass: 64, 90 in final positions ✓\n\n--- Pass 3 (i=2) ---\n  j=0: compare 25,12 → swap → [12, 25, 22, 11, 34, 64, 90]\n  j=1: compare 25,22 → swap → [12, 22, 25, 11, 34, 64, 90]\n  j=2: compare 25,11 → swap → [12, 22, 11, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n  j=3: compare 25,34 → ok   → [12, 22, 11, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n  End of pass: 34, 64, 90 in final positions ✓\n\n--- Pass 4 (i=3) ---\n  j=0: compare 12,22 → ok   → [12, 22, 11, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n  j=1: compare 22,11 → swap → [12, 11, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n  j=2: compare 22,25 → ok   → [12, 11, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n\n--- Pass 5 (i=4) ---\n  j=0: compare 12,11 → swap → [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n  j=1: compare 12,22 → ok   → [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n\n--- Pass 6 (i=5) ---\n  j=0: compare 11,12 → ok   → no swaps → EARLY EXIT\n\nFinal: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90] ✓\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2. Selection Sort\n\n### Algorithm Description\n\nSelection Sort divides the array into a sorted left portion and an unsorted right portion. On each pass, it **selects** the minimum element from the unsorted portion and moves it to the end of the sorted portion by swapping.\n\n**Steps:**\n1. Set the boundary between sorted and unsorted at index 0.\n2. Scan the entire unsorted portion to find the index of the minimum element.\n3. Swap that minimum element with the first element of the unsorted portion.\n4. Advance the boundary by 1 (the sorted portion grows by one element).\n5. Repeat until the boundary reaches the last element.\n\n### Complexity Analysis\n\n| Case | Time | Why |\n|------|------|-----|\n| Best | O(n²) | Must scan entire unsorted portion regardless — no early exit |\n| Average | O(n²) | Always does n(n-1)/2 comparisons |\n| Worst | O(n²) | Same — always scans fully |\n| **Space** | **O(1)** | In-place; only index variables |\n\n**Key insight:** Selection Sort always performs exactly `n(n-1)/2` comparisons but at most `n-1` swaps. This makes it useful when writes are expensive (e.g., flash memory), unlike Bubble Sort which can do O(n²) swaps.\n\n### Python Implementation\n\n```python\ndef selection_sort(arr):\n    n = len(arr)\n    \n    # i is the boundary: arr[0..i-1] is sorted, arr[i..n-1] is unsorted\n    for i in range(n):\n        \n        # Assume the first element of the unsorted portion is the minimum\n        min_idx = i\n        \n        # Scan the rest of the unsorted portion for a smaller element\n        for j in range(i + 1, n):\n            if arr[j] < arr[min_idx]:\n                min_idx = j  # Found a new minimum; record its index\n        \n        # If the minimum is not already at position i, swap it there.\n        # This is the key advantage: at most one swap per pass.\n        if min_idx != i:\n            arr[i], arr[min_idx] = arr[min_idx], arr[i]\n        \n        # After this iteration, arr[0..i] is sorted and in final positions\n    \n    return arr\n```\n\n### Example Trace: `[64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]`\n\n```\nInitial:  [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]\n           ^--- unsorted starts here\n\n--- Pass 1 (i=0): find min of [64,34,25,12,22,11,90] ---\n  Scan: min=64(idx=0) → 34 < 64, min=34(idx=1) → 25 < 34, min=25(idx=2)\n        → 12 < 25, min=12(idx=3) → 22 > 12 → 11 < 12, min=11(idx=5) → 90 > 11\n  Minimum is 11 at index 5. Swap arr[0] ↔ arr[5]:\n  [11, 34, 25, 12, 22, 64, 90]\n   ✓\n\n--- Pass 2 (i=1): find min of [34,25,12,22,64,90] ---\n  Scan: min=34(idx=1) → 25<34, min=25(idx=2) → 12<25, min=12(idx=3)\n        → 22>12 → 64>12 → 90>12\n  Minimum is 12 at index 3. Swap arr[1] ↔ arr[3]:\n  [11, 12, 25, 34, 22, 64, 90]\n       ✓\n\n--- Pass 3 (i=2): find min of [25,34,22,64,90] ---\n  Scan: min=25(idx=2) → 34>25 → 22<25, min=22(idx=4) → 64>22 → 90>22\n  Minimum is 22 at index 4. Swap arr[2] ↔ arr[4]:\n  [11, 12, 22, 34, 25, 64, 90]\n           ✓\n\n--- Pass 4 (i=3): find min of [34,25,64,90] ---\n  Scan: min=34(idx=3) → 25<34, min=25(idx=4) → 64>25 → 90>25\n  Minimum is 25 at index 4. Swap arr[3] ↔ arr[4]:\n  [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n               ✓\n\n--- Pass 5 (i=4): find min of [34,64,90] ---\n  Scan: min=34(idx=4) → 64>34 → 90>34\n  Minimum already at index 4. No swap needed.\n  [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n                   ✓\n\n--- Pass 6 (i=5): find min of [64,90] ---\n  Scan: min=64(idx=5) → 90>64\n  Minimum already at index 5. No swap.\n  [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n                       ✓\n\nFinal: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90] ✓\nTotal swaps: 4 (much fewer than Bubble Sort's swaps)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. Insertion Sort\n\n### Algorithm Description\n\nInsertion Sort builds the sorted array one element at a time by taking each new element and **inserting** it into its correct position among the already-sorted elements to its left — like sorting a hand of playing cards.\n\n**Steps:**\n1. Consider `arr[0]` as a sorted sub-array of length 1.\n2. Take `arr[1]` (the \"key\"). Compare it against `arr[0]`. If smaller, shift `arr[0]` right and insert key at position 0.\n3. Take `arr[2]`. Compare against sorted portion `arr[0..1]`. Shift elements right until finding the correct insertion point.\n4. Continue for each element `arr[i]`, scanning left and shifting until the correct position is found.\n5. After processing `arr[n-1]`, the entire array is sorted.\n\n### Complexity Analysis\n\n| Case | Time | Why |\n|------|------|-----|\n| Best | O(n) | Already sorted — each element is already ≥ its left neighbor, inner loop never runs |\n| Average | O(n²) | Each insertion scans ~half the sorted portion |\n| Worst | O(n²) | Reverse-sorted — each element must travel all the way to position 0 |\n| **Space** | **O(1)** | In-place; one `key` variable |\n\n**Key insight:** Insertion Sort is adaptive (faster on nearly-sorted data), stable, and extremely fast on small arrays (n < 20). It's used as the base case in hybrid algorithms like TimSort (Python's built-in sort).\n\n### Python Implementation\n\n```python\ndef insertion_sort(arr):\n    # Start from index 1; arr[0] is trivially \"sorted\" on its own\n    for i in range(1, len(arr)):\n        \n        # key is the element we are currently trying to insert\n        # into its correct position in the sorted left portion\n        key = arr[i]\n        \n        # j starts just to the left of key's current position\n        j = i - 1\n        \n        # Shift elements of arr[0..i-1] that are greater than key\n        # one position to the right to make room for key.\n        # This loop moves left until it finds arr[j] <= key or runs out of space.\n        while j >= 0 and arr[j] > key:\n            arr[j + 1] = arr[j]  # shift element right\n            j -= 1\n        \n        # j+1 is now the correct position for key:\n        # arr[j] <= key (or j == -1, meaning key is smallest seen so far)\n        arr[j + 1] = key\n    \n    return arr\n```\n\n### Example Trace: `[64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]`\n\n```\nInitial:  [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]\n\n--- i=1, key=34 ---\n  Sorted portion: [64]\n  j=0: arr[0]=64 > 34 → shift 64 right → [64, 64, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]\n  j=-1: stop. Insert key=34 at index 0.\n  Result: [34, 64, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]\n           ^^sorted^^\n\n--- i=2, key=25 ---\n  Sorted portion: [34, 64]\n  j=1: arr[1]=64 > 25 → shift → [34, 64, 64, 12, 22, 11, 90]\n  j=0: arr[0]=34 > 25 → shift → [34, 34, 64, 12, 22, 11, 90]\n  j=-1: stop. Insert key=25 at index 0.\n  Result: [25, 34, 64, 12, 22, 11, 90]\n           ^^^^^^^sorted^^^^^^^\n\n--- i=3, key=12 ---\n  Sorted portion: [25, 34, 64]\n  j=2: 64 > 12 → shift → [25, 34, 64, 64, 22, 11, 90]\n  j=1: 34 > 12 → shift → [25, 34, 34, 64, 22, 11, 90]\n  j=0: 25 > 12 → shift → [25, 25, 34, 64, 22, 11, 90]\n  j=-1: stop. Insert key=12 at index 0.\n  Result: [12, 25, 34, 64, 22, 11, 90]\n\n--- i=4, key=22 ---\n  Sorted portion: [12, 25, 34, 64]\n  j=3: 64 > 22 → shift → [12, 25, 34, 64, 64, 11, 90]\n  j=2: 34 > 22 → shift → [12, 25, 34, 34, 64, 11, 90]\n  j=1: 25 > 22 → shift → [12, 25, 25, 34, 64, 11, 90]\n  j=0: 12 ≤ 22 → stop. Insert key=22 at index 1.\n  Result: [12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 11, 90]\n\n--- i=5, key=11 ---\n  Sorted portion: [12, 22, 25, 34, 64]\n  j=4: 64>11 → j=3: 34>11 → j=2: 25>11 → j=1: 22>11 → j=0: 12>11 → j=-1\n  Shift all right, insert 11 at index 0.\n  Result: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n\n--- i=6, key=90 ---\n  Sorted portion: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64]\n  j=5: arr[5]=64 ≤ 90 → stop immediately. Insert at index 6 (no movement).\n  Result: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n\nFinal: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90] ✓\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Merge Sort\n\n### Algorithm Description\n\nMerge Sort is a classic **divide-and-conquer** algorithm. It recursively splits the array in half, sorts each half independently, then **merges** the two sorted halves into a single sorted array.\n\n**Steps:**\n1. **Base case:** If the array has 0 or 1 elements, it is already sorted — return it.\n2. **Divide:** Find the midpoint `mid = n // 2`. Split into `left = arr[:mid]` and `right = arr[mid:]`.\n3. **Conquer:** Recursively call merge sort on `left` and on `right`.\n4. **Merge:** Combine the two sorted halves:\n   - Maintain a pointer `i` into `left` and `j` into `right`.\n   - Repeatedly compare `left[i]` and `right[j]`, appending the smaller to the result.\n   - Append any remaining elements from whichever half isn't exhausted.\n5. Return the merged result.\n\n### Complexity Analysis\n\n| Case | Time | Why |\n|------|------|-----|\n| Best | O(n log n) | Divide step always produces log n levels regardless of input |\n| Average | O(n log n) | Same — structure is always a balanced binary recursion tree |\n| Worst | O(n log n) | Same — guaranteed, unlike Quick Sort |\n| **Space** | **O(n)** | Each merge step requires a temporary array to hold merged output |\n\n**Key insight:** The recursion tree has log₂(n) levels. At each level, the total work done across all merge operations is O(n) (every element is processed once). Therefore: O(n) × O(log n) = O(n log n). This is optimal for comparison-based sorting.\n\n### Python Implementation\n\n```python\ndef merge_sort(arr):\n    # Base case: a single element (or empty array) is already sorted\n    if len(arr) <= 1:\n        return arr\n    \n    # --- DIVIDE ---\n    # Find the midpoint to split the array into two halves\n    mid = len(arr) // 2\n    left_half = arr[:mid]   # elements from index 0 to mid-1\n    right_half = arr[mid:]  # elements from index mid to end\n    \n    # --- CONQUER ---\n    # Recursively sort each half.\n    # These calls keep splitting until base case is reached,\n    # then the sorted sub-arrays \"bubble up\" through the return values.\n    left_sorted = merge_sort(left_half)\n    right_sorted = merge_sort(right_half)\n    \n    # --- MERGE ---\n    # Combine two sorted halves into one sorted array\n    return merge(left_sorted, right_sorted)\n\n\ndef merge(left, right):\n    \"\"\"Merge two sorted arrays into one sorted array.\"\"\"\n    result = []\n    i = 0  # pointer into left array\n    j = 0  # pointer into right array\n    \n    # Compare front elements of each array; take the smaller one\n    while i < len(left) and j < len(right):\n        if left[i] <= right[j]:\n            # <= ensures stability: equal elements from left come first\n            result.append(left[i])\n            i += 1\n        else:\n            result.append(right[j])\n            j += 1\n    \n    # One of the arrays may have remaining elements.\n    # Since both are sorted, we can safely append the rest.\n    result.extend(left[i:])   # append leftover from left (may be empty)\n    result.extend(right[j:])  # append leftover from right (may be empty)\n    \n    return result\n```\n\n### Example Trace: `[64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]`\n\n```\nmerge_sort([64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90])\n│\n├─ DIVIDE at mid=3\n│   left  = [64, 34, 25]\n│   right = [12, 22, 11, 90]\n│\n├─ merge_sort([64, 34, 25])\n│   ├─ DIVIDE at mid=1\n│   │   left=[64], right=[34, 25]\n│   ├─ merge_sort([64]) → [64]  (base case)\n│   ├─ merge_sort([34, 25])\n│   │   ├─ DIVIDE at mid=1: left=[34], right=[25]\n│   │   ├─ merge_sort([34]) → [34]  (base case)\n│   │   ├─ merge_sort([25]) → [25]  (base case)\n│   │   └─ merge([34],[25]):\n│   │       i=0,j=0: 34 > 25 → take 25. result=[25], j=1\n│   │       j exhausted. Extend with left[0:]: [34]\n│   │       → [25, 34]\n│   └─ merge([64],[25,34]):\n│       i=0,j=0: 64 > 25 → take 25. result=[25], j=1\n│       i=0,j=1: 64 > 34 → take 34. result=[25,34], j=2\n│       j exhausted. Extend with left[0:]: [64]\n│       → [25, 34, 64]\n│\n├─ merge_sort([12, 22, 11, 90])\n│   ├─ DIVIDE at mid=2: left=[12,22], right=[11,90]\n│   ├─ merge_sort([12, 22])\n│   │   ├─ DIVIDE: left=[12], right=[22]\n│   │   ├─ merge([12],[22]):\n│   │   │   12 ≤ 22 → take 12. Extend [22]. → [12, 22]\n│   └─ merge_sort([11, 90])\n│       ├─ DIVIDE: left=[11], right=[90]\n│       ├─ merge([11],[90]):\n│       │   11 ≤ 90 → take 11. Extend [90]. → [11, 90]\n│   └─ merge([12,22],[11,90]):\n│       i=0,j=0: 12 > 11 → take 11. result=[11], j=1\n│       i=0,j=1: 12 ≤ 90 → take 12. result=[11,12], i=1\n│       i=1,j=1: 22 ≤ 90 → take 22. result=[11,12,22], i=2\n│       i exhausted. Extend [90]. → [11, 12, 22, 90]\n│\n└─ merge([25,34,64],[11,12,22,90]):\n    i=0,j=0: 25 > 11 → take 11. result=[11]\n    i=0,j=1: 25 > 12 → take 12. result=[11,12]\n    i=0,j=2: 25 > 22 → take 22. result=[11,12,22]\n    i=0,j=3: 25 ≤ 90 → take 25. result=[11,12,22,25]\n    i=1,j=3: 34 ≤ 90 → take 34. result=[11,12,22,25,34]\n    i=2,j=3: 64 ≤ 90 → take 64. result=[11,12,22,25,34,64]\n    i exhausted. Extend [90]. → [11,12,22,25,34,64,90]\n\nFinal: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90] ✓\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Quick Sort\n\n### Algorithm Description\n\nQuick Sort is another divide-and-conquer algorithm. It selects a **pivot** element and **partitions** the array so that all elements less than the pivot are to its left, and all greater are to its right. The pivot is now in its final sorted position. Quick Sort then recurses on the left and right sub-arrays.\n\n**Steps:**\n1. **Choose pivot:** Select an element (here: last element). Common alternatives: first, random, or median-of-three.\n2. **Partition:**\n   - Maintain a \"store index\" `i` starting before the array.\n   - Scan from left to right. For each element smaller than pivot, increment `i` and swap `arr[i]` with `arr[j]`.\n   - After scanning, swap pivot from its position (`arr[high]`) into position `i+1`.\n   - The pivot is now at its final sorted index.\n3. **Recurse:** Apply Quick Sort to `arr[low..pivot_idx-1]` and `arr[pivot_idx+1..high]`.\n4. **Base case:** When the sub-array has 0 or 1 elements, it is sorted.\n\n### Complexity Analysis\n\n| Case | Time | Why |\n|------|------|-----|\n| Best | O(n log n) | Pivot always splits array in half — balanced recursion tree |\n| Average | O(n log n) | Expected with random data; on average, partitions are near-balanced |\n| Worst | O(n²) | Pivot always smallest/largest (sorted input with first/last pivot) — tree degenerates to a linked list |\n| **Space** | **O(log n)** | Recursive call stack depth. O(n) in worst case |\n\n**Key insight:** Despite the same asymptotic complexity as Merge Sort, Quick Sort is usually faster in practice because it has better cache locality (sorts in-place), lower constant factors, and no extra memory allocation. The worst case is avoided by randomizing pivot selection.\n\n### Python Implementation\n\n```python\ndef quick_sort(arr, low=0, high=None):\n    # Initialize high to last index on first call\n    if high is None:\n        high = len(arr) - 1\n    \n    # Base case: sub-array of size 0 or 1 is already sorted\n    if low < high:\n        # Partition the array and get the pivot's final index\n        pivot_index = partition(arr, low, high)\n        \n        # Recursively sort elements before and after the pivot.\n        # The pivot itself is already in its final position.\n        quick_sort(arr, low, pivot_index - 1)   # sort left sub-array\n        quick_sort(arr, pivot_index + 1, high)  # sort right sub-array\n    \n    return arr\n\n\ndef partition(arr, low, high):\n    \"\"\"\n    Lomuto partition scheme:\n    - Uses arr[high] as pivot.\n    - Rearranges arr[low..high] so elements < pivot are left of pivot,\n      elements > pivot are right. Returns pivot's final index.\n    \"\"\"\n    pivot = arr[high]  # choose last element as pivot\n    \n    # i is the index of the last element known to be <= pivot.\n    # It starts at low-1 (no elements confirmed yet).\n    i = low - 1\n    \n    # Scan every element except the pivot itself\n    for j in range(low, high):\n        # If current element is less than or equal to pivot,\n        # it belongs in the left partition\n        if arr[j] <= pivot:\n            i += 1\n            # Swap arr[j] into the left partition\n            arr[i], arr[j] = arr[j], arr[i]\n    \n    # Place pivot in its final position: just after the left partition\n    arr[i + 1], arr[high] = arr[high], arr[i + 1]\n    \n    # Return the pivot's final sorted index\n    return i + 1\n```\n\n### Example Trace: `[64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]`\n\n```\nquick_sort([64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90], low=0, high=6)\n\n--- PARTITION (low=0, high=6): pivot = arr[6] = 90 ---\n  i = -1\n  j=0: arr[0]=64 ≤ 90 → i=0, swap arr[0]↔arr[0] (no-op) → [64,34,25,12,22,11,90]\n  j=1: arr[1]=34 ≤ 90 → i=1, swap arr[1]↔arr[1] (no-op) → [64,34,25,12,22,11,90]\n  j=2: arr[2]=25 ≤ 90 → i=2, swap → [64,34,25,12,22,11,90]\n  j=3: arr[3]=12 ≤ 90 → i=3, swap → [64,34,25,12,22,11,90]\n  j=4: arr[4]=22 ≤ 90 → i=4, swap → [64,34,25,12,22,11,90]\n  j=5: arr[5]=11 ≤ 90 → i=5, swap → [64,34,25,12,22,11,90]\n  Place pivot: swap arr[6] ↔ arr[6] → pivot_index = 6\n  Array: [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, | 90 |]\n                                      ✓ 90 in final position\n\n  Recurse LEFT:  quick_sort(arr, 0, 5) on [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11]\n  Recurse RIGHT: quick_sort(arr, 7, 6) → low > high → base case, done\n\n--- PARTITION (low=0, high=5): pivot = arr[5] = 11 ---\n  i = -1\n  j=0: 64 > 11 → no swap\n  j=1: 34 > 11 → no swap\n  j=2: 25 > 11 → no swap\n  j=3: 12 > 11 → no swap\n  j=4: 22 > 11 → no swap\n  Place pivot: swap arr[0] ↔ arr[5] → [11, 34, 25, 12, 22, 64, 90]\n  pivot_index = 0\n  Array: [| 11 | 34, 25, 12, 22, 64, 90]\n             ✓ 11 in final position\n\n  LEFT:  quick_sort(arr, 0, -1) → base case\n  RIGHT: quick_sort(arr, 1, 5) on [34, 25, 12, 22, 64]\n\n--- PARTITION (low=1, high=5): pivot = arr[5] = 64 ---\n  i=0\n  j=1: 34≤64 → i=1, swap arr[1]↔arr[1] → [11,34,25,12,22,64,90]\n  j=2: 25≤64 → i=2, swap → [11,34,25,12,22,64,90]\n  j=3: 12≤64 → i=3, swap → [11,34,25,12,22,64,90]\n  j=4: 22≤64 → i=4, swap → [11,34,25,12,22,64,90]\n  Place pivot: swap arr[5]↔arr[5] → pivot_index=5\n  Array: [11, 34, 25, 12, 22, | 64 | 90]\n                                  ✓ 64 in final position\n\n  RIGHT: quick_sort(arr, 6, 5) → base case\n  LEFT:  quick_sort(arr, 1, 4) on [34, 25, 12, 22]\n\n--- PARTITION (low=1, high=4): pivot = arr[4] = 22 ---\n  i=0\n  j=1: 34>22 → no swap\n  j=2: 25>22 → no swap\n  j=3: 12≤22 → i=1, swap arr[1]↔arr[3] → [11,12,25,34,22,64,90]\n  Place pivot: swap arr[2]↔arr[4] → [11,12,22,34,25,64,90]\n  pivot_index=2\n  Array: [11, 12, | 22 | 34, 25, 64, 90]\n                     ✓ 22 in final position\n\n  LEFT:  quick_sort(arr, 1, 1) → base case (single element 12) ✓\n  RIGHT: quick_sort(arr, 3, 4) on [34, 25]\n\n--- PARTITION (low=3, high=4): pivot = arr[4] = 25 ---\n  i=2\n  j=3: 34>25 → no swap\n  Place pivot: swap arr[3]↔arr[4] → [11,12,22,25,34,64,90]\n  pivot_index=3\n  Array: [11, 12, 22, | 25 | 34, 64, 90]\n                         ✓ 25 in final position\n\n  LEFT:  quick_sort(arr, 3, 2) → base case\n  RIGHT: quick_sort(arr, 4, 4) → base case (34) ✓\n\nFinal: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90] ✓\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Heap Sort\n\n### Algorithm Description\n\nHeap Sort uses a **binary max-heap** data structure. A max-heap is a complete binary tree where every parent is greater than or equal to its children, so the maximum element is always at the root. Heap Sort has two phases:\n\n**Phase 1 — Build Max-Heap:**\n- Transform the unsorted array in-place into a max-heap using a process called \"heapification\".\n- Start from the last non-leaf node (index `n//2 - 1`) and call `heapify` on each node down to index 0.\n- `heapify(arr, n, i)`: ensures the subtree rooted at index `i` satisfies heap property by comparing `arr[i]` against its children and sinking it down if needed.\n\n**Phase 2 — Extract Max Repeatedly:**\n- The root `arr[0]` is always the largest element in the heap.\n- Swap `arr[0]` with the last element `arr[n-1]`. Now the largest is at the end (in its final position).\n- Shrink the heap by 1 (ignore the last element) and call `heapify` on the new root to restore heap property.\n- Repeat until the heap has one element.\n\n### Complexity Analysis\n\n| Case | Time | Why |\n|------|------|-----|\n| Best | O(n log n) | Build heap is O(n); each of n-1 extractions takes O(log n) |\n| Average | O(n log n) | Same structure regardless of input |\n| Worst | O(n log n) | Guaranteed — no degenerate cases unlike Quick Sort |\n| **Space** | **O(1)** | In-place; heap is built within the array itself |\n\n**Key insight:** For a heap of size n, the height is ⌊log₂n⌋. Heapify takes O(log n) because in the worst case an element sinks all the way from root to a leaf. Building the heap is O(n) (not O(n log n)) because most nodes are near the bottom and sink very little.\n\n**Array index formulas** (0-indexed):\n- Left child of `i`: `2*i + 1`\n- Right child of `i`: `2*i + 2`\n- Parent of `i`: `(i - 1) // 2`\n\n### Python Implementation\n\n```python\ndef heap_sort(arr):\n    n = len(arr)\n    \n    # === PHASE 1: Build a max-heap from the unsorted array ===\n    # Start from the last non-leaf node and heapify downward.\n    # Leaves (indices n//2 to n-1) are trivially valid heaps of size 1.\n    # The last non-leaf is at index n//2 - 1.\n    for i in range(n // 2 - 1, -1, -1):\n        heapify(arr, n, i)\n    \n    # === PHASE 2: Extract elements from the heap one by one ===\n    for i in range(n - 1, 0, -1):\n        # The current root arr[0] is the maximum of the remaining heap.\n        # Move it to its final sorted position at arr[i].\n        arr[0], arr[i] = arr[i], arr[0]\n        \n        # The heap now has one fewer element (size shrinks by 1 each iteration).\n        # Restore heap property for the reduced heap rooted at index 0.\n        heapify(arr, i, 0)\n    \n    return arr\n\n\ndef heapify(arr, heap_size, root):\n    \"\"\"\n    Ensures the subtree rooted at `root` satisfies max-heap property.\n    `heap_size` is how many elements are considered part of the heap.\n    Sinks arr[root] down until it is >= both its children.\n    \"\"\"\n    largest = root           # assume root is largest among root and its children\n    left  = 2 * root + 1    # index of left child\n    right = 2 * root + 2    # index of right child\n    \n    # Check if left child exists and is larger than current 'largest'\n    if left < heap_size and arr[left] > arr[largest]:\n        largest = left\n    \n    # Check if right child exists and is larger than current 'largest'\n    if right < heap_size and arr[right] > arr[largest]:\n        largest = right\n    \n    # If largest is not the root, the heap property is violated — fix it\n    if largest != root:\n        # Swap root with the larger child\n        arr[root], arr[largest] = arr[largest], arr[root]\n        \n        # The child that we moved root into may now violate heap property.\n        # Recursively heapify the affected subtree.\n        heapify(arr, heap_size, largest)\n```\n\n### Example Trace: `[64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]`\n\n```\nInitial array: [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]\nVisualized as tree (index: value):\n           64(0)\n          /      \\\n       34(1)    25(2)\n       /   \\    /   \\\n    12(3) 22(4) 11(5) 90(6)\n\nn=7, last non-leaf = 7//2 - 1 = 2\n\n=== PHASE 1: BUILD MAX-HEAP ===\n\n--- heapify(arr, 7, i=2): root=25, left=11(5), right=90(6) ---\n  largest = 2 (25)\n  arr[5]=11 < arr[2]=25 → largest stays 2\n  arr[6]=90 > arr[2]=25 → largest = 6\n  Swap arr[2] ↔ arr[6]: [64, 34, 90, 12, 22, 11, 25]\n  Recurse heapify(arr, 7, 6): no children → done\n  Tree:         64\n               /    \\\n             34      90\n            /  \\    /  \\\n          12   22  11   25\n\n--- heapify(arr, 7, i=1): root=34, left=12(3), right=22(4) ---\n  arr[3]=12 < 34, arr[4]=22 < 34 → largest = 1 (root)\n  No swap needed.\n\n--- heapify(arr, 7, i=0): root=64, left=34(1), right=90(2) ---\n  arr[2]=90 > arr[0]=64 → largest = 2\n  Swap arr[0] ↔ arr[2]: [90, 34, 64, 12, 22, 11, 25]\n  Recurse heapify(arr, 7, 2): root=64, left=11(5), right=25(6)\n    64 > 11, 64 > 25 → no swap\n  Tree:         90        ← MAX-HEAP BUILT ✓\n               /    \\\n             34      64\n            /  \\    /  \\\n          12   22  11   25\n\n=== PHASE 2: EXTRACT MAX REPEATEDLY ===\n\n--- i=6: swap arr[0]↔arr[6] → [25, 34, 64, 12, 22, 11, |90|] ---\n  Heap (size=6): [25, 34, 64, 12, 22, 11]\n  heapify(arr, 6, 0): root=25, left=34(1), right=64(2)\n    64 > 25 → largest=2\n    Swap arr[0]↔arr[2]: [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]\n    Recurse heapify(arr, 6, 2): root=25, left=11(5) only (6 is out of heap)\n      11 < 25 → no swap\n  Heap: [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11]  Sorted tail: [90]\n\n--- i=5: swap arr[0]↔arr[5] → [11, 34, 25, 12, 22, |64|, 90] ---\n  heapify(arr, 5, 0): root=11, left=34(1), right=25(2)\n    34 > 11 → largest=1\n    Swap arr[0]↔arr[1]: [34, 11, 25, 12, 22, 64, 90]\n    Recurse heapify(arr, 5, 1): root=11, left=12(3), right=22(4)\n      22 > 11 → largest=4\n      Swap arr[1]↔arr[4]: [34, 22, 25, 12, 11, 64, 90]\n      Recurse heapify(arr, 5, 4): index 4 has no children in heap of size 5 (left=9≥5) → done\n  Heap: [34, 22, 25, 12, 11]  Sorted: [64, 90]\n\n--- i=4: swap arr[0]↔arr[4] → [11, 22, 25, 12, |34|, 64, 90] ---\n  heapify(arr, 4, 0): root=11, left=22(1), right=25(2)\n    25 > 11 → largest=2\n    Swap arr[0]↔arr[2]: [25, 22, 11, 12, 34, 64, 90]\n    Recurse heapify(arr, 4, 2): left=5(5)≥4, right=6≥4 → no children in heap → done\n  Heap: [25, 22, 11, 12]  Sorted: [34, 64, 90]\n\n--- i=3: swap arr[0]↔arr[3] → [12, 22, 11, |25|, 34, 64, 90] ---\n  heapify(arr, 3, 0): root=12, left=22(1), right=11(2)\n    22 > 12 → largest=1\n    Swap arr[0]↔arr[1]: [22, 12, 11, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n    Recurse heapify(arr, 3, 1): left=3≥3 → no children → done\n  Heap: [22, 12, 11]  Sorted: [25, 34, 64, 90]\n\n--- i=2: swap arr[0]↔arr[2] → [11, 12, |22|, 25, 34, 64, 90] ---\n  heapify(arr, 2, 0): root=11, left=12(1), right would be index 2 (out of heap)\n    12 > 11 → largest=1\n    Swap arr[0]↔arr[1]: [12, 11, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n    Recurse heapify(arr, 2, 1): no children → done\n  Heap: [12, 11]  Sorted: [22, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n\n--- i=1: swap arr[0]↔arr[1] → [11, |12|, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90] ---\n  heapify(arr, 1, 0): heap size=1, no children → done\n\nFinal: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90] ✓\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Counting Sort\n\n### Algorithm Description\n\nCounting Sort is a **non-comparison-based** sorting algorithm. Instead of comparing elements to each other, it counts how many times each distinct value appears, then reconstructs the sorted output from those counts.\n\n**Steps:**\n1. **Find range:** Determine the minimum and maximum values in the input to size the count array.\n2. **Count occurrences:** Create a count array `count[0..k]` where `k = max - min`. For each element `x`, increment `count[x - min]`.\n3. **Cumulative counts (for stable sort):** Transform `count` so that `count[i]` holds the number of elements ≤ `min + i`. This gives the ending position index of each value in the output.\n4. **Build output:** Traverse the input array right-to-left (for stability). Place each element `x` at output index `count[x - min] - 1`, then decrement that count.\n5. Copy output back to original array.\n\n### Complexity Analysis\n\n| Case | Time | Why |\n|------|------|-----|\n| Best | O(n + k) | One pass to count, one pass to output; k = range of values |\n| Average | O(n + k) | Same |\n| Worst | O(n + k) | Same — completely independent of element ordering |\n| **Space** | **O(n + k)** | Count array of size k+1 plus output array of size n |\n\n**Key insight:** When `k = O(n)` (range is proportional to input size), Counting Sort runs in O(n) — faster than any comparison-based sort's Ω(n log n) lower bound. However, if `k` is huge (e.g., sorting 5 numbers in range 0..10⁹), the O(k) overhead makes it impractical.\n\n### Python Implementation\n\n```python\ndef counting_sort(arr):\n    if not arr:\n        return arr\n    \n    # === STEP 1: Find the range of input values ===\n    min_val = min(arr)\n    max_val = max(arr)\n    range_size = max_val - min_val + 1  # number of distinct possible values\n    \n    # === STEP 2: Count occurrences of each value ===\n    # count[i] = how many times (min_val + i) appears in arr\n    count = [0] * range_size\n    for num in arr:\n        count[num - min_val] += 1\n    \n    # === STEP 3: Compute cumulative counts ===\n    # After this, count[i] = number of elements <= (min_val + i)\n    # This tells us the last valid output index for each value.\n    for i in range(1, range_size):\n        count[i] += count[i - 1]\n    \n    # === STEP 4: Build the output array (right-to-left for stability) ===\n    # Traversing right-to-left ensures that equal elements appear in the\n    # same relative order in the output as in the input (stable sort).\n    output = [0] * len(arr)\n    for num in reversed(arr):\n        idx = num - min_val               # map value to count index\n        output[count[idx] - 1] = num      # place at computed position\n        count[idx] -= 1                   # decrement so next equal element goes one earlier\n    \n    # === STEP 5: Copy sorted output back to original array ===\n    for i in range(len(arr)):\n        arr[i] = output[i]\n    \n    return arr\n```\n\n### Example Trace: `[64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]`\n\n```\nInput: [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]\n\nSTEP 1: min=11, max=90, range_size = 90-11+1 = 80\n\nSTEP 2: Count occurrences (showing only non-zero entries)\n  count array has indices 0..79 (representing values 11..90)\n  index = value - 11:\n  \n  value 11 → index  0: count[0]  = 1\n  value 12 → index  1: count[1]  = 1\n  value 22 → index 11: count[11] = 1\n  value 25 → index 14: count[14] = 1\n  value 34 → index 23: count[23] = 1\n  value 64 → index 53: count[53] = 1\n  value 90 → index 79: count[79] = 1\n  All others = 0\n\nSTEP 3: Cumulative counts\n  count[0]  = 1  (1 element ≤ 11)\n  count[1]  = 2  (2 elements ≤ 12)\n  count[2..10] = 2  (still 2 elements ≤ 13..21)\n  count[11] = 3  (3 elements ≤ 22)\n  count[12..13] = 3\n  count[14] = 4  (4 elements ≤ 25)\n  ...\n  count[23] = 5  (5 elements ≤ 34)\n  ...\n  count[53] = 6  (6 elements ≤ 64)\n  ...\n  count[79] = 7  (7 elements ≤ 90)\n\nSTEP 4: Build output (traverse input right-to-left)\n  output = [0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]\n\n  num=90 → idx=79, count[79]=7, place at output[6]=90, count[79]=6\n  output: [0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 90]\n\n  num=11 → idx=0, count[0]=1, place at output[0]=11, count[0]=0\n  output: [11, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 90]\n\n  num=22 → idx=11, count[11]=3, place at output[2]=22, count[11]=2\n  output: [11, 0, 22, 0, 0, 0, 90]\n\n  num=12 → idx=1, count[1]=2, place at output[1]=12, count[1]=1\n  output: [11, 12, 22, 0, 0, 0, 90]\n\n  num=25 → idx=14, count[14]=4, place at output[3]=25, count[14]=3\n  output: [11, 12, 22, 25, 0, 0, 90]\n\n  num=34 → idx=23, count[23]=5, place at output[4]=34, count[23]=4\n  output: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 0, 90]\n\n  num=64 → idx=53, count[53]=6, place at output[5]=64, count[53]=5\n  output: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n\nSTEP 5: Copy back\nFinal: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90] ✓\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Radix Sort\n\n### Algorithm Description\n\nRadix Sort is a **non-comparison-based** algorithm that sorts integers digit by digit, from least significant digit (LSD) to most significant digit (MSD). It uses a stable sub-sort (Counting Sort) at each digit position.\n\n**Steps (LSD Radix Sort):**\n1. Find the maximum value to determine the number of digits `d`.\n2. For each digit position `exp` (1s, 10s, 100s, ...):\n   a. Extract the digit of each element at position `exp`: `(num // exp) % 10`\n   b. Apply a **stable** counting sort based only on that digit (0–9).\n   c. The stable sort preserves relative order of elements with equal digits — this is critical for correctness.\n3. After processing all digit positions, the array is fully sorted.\n\n**Why does it work?** Because the sub-sort is stable, when we sort by the tens digit, elements with the same tens digit remain sorted by their units digit (sorted in a previous pass). Stability at each level \"accumulates\" the sort across all digit positions.\n\n### Complexity Analysis\n\n| Case | Time | Why |\n|------|------|-----|\n| Best | O(d × (n + b)) | d passes of Counting Sort; b=base (10) |\n| Average | O(d × (n + b)) | Same |\n| Worst | O(d × (n + b)) | Same — fully predictable |\n| **Space** | **O(n + b)** | Output array of size n; count array of size b=10 |\n\nWhere `d = number of digits in max value ≈ log_b(max_val)`.\n\n**Key insight:** When `d` is constant or small (e.g., sorting 32-bit integers, `d=10` with base 10), Radix Sort runs in O(n) time. It beats comparison-based sorts when `d × b = O(n)`. The trade-off is it only works on integers (or strings of fixed length).\n\n### Python Implementation\n\n```python\ndef radix_sort(arr):\n    if not arr:\n        return arr\n    \n    # Find the maximum number to determine how many digit positions to process\n    max_val = max(arr)\n    \n    # Process each digit position: units (exp=1), tens (exp=10), hundreds (exp=100), ...\n    # Stop when exp exceeds max_val (no more significant digits)\n    exp = 1\n    while max_val // exp > 0:\n        counting_sort_by_digit(arr, exp)\n        exp *= 10\n    \n    return arr\n\n\ndef counting_sort_by_digit(arr, exp):\n    \"\"\"\n    Stable sort of arr based only on the digit at position `exp`.\n    exp=1   → sort by units digit\n    exp=10  → sort by tens digit\n    exp=100 → sort by hundreds digit, etc.\n    \"\"\"\n    n = len(arr)\n    output = [0] * n\n    \n    # count[d] = number of elements whose digit at `exp` equals d\n    # Digits range from 0-9, so count has size 10 (the base)\n    count = [0] * 10\n    \n    # === Count occurrences of each digit ===\n    for num in arr:\n        digit = (num // exp) % 10  # extract the relevant digit\n        count[digit] += 1\n    \n    # === Cumulative count ===\n    # count[d] now = number of elements with digit <= d\n    for i in range(1, 10):\n        count[i] += count[i - 1]\n    \n    # === Build output (right-to-left for stability) ===\n    # Traversing right-to-left maintains relative order of equal-digit elements.\n    for num in reversed(arr):\n        digit = (num // exp) % 10\n        output[count[digit] - 1] = num\n        count[digit] -= 1\n    \n    # Copy sorted output back to arr\n    for i in range(n):\n        arr[i] = output[i]\n```\n\n### Example Trace: `[64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]`\n\n```\nInput: [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]\nmax_val = 90 → 2 digits → 2 passes (exp=1, exp=10)\n\n══════════════════════════════════════════\nPASS 1 (exp=1): Sort by UNITS digit\n══════════════════════════════════════════\n\nExtract units digits:\n  64→4,  34→4,  25→5,  12→2,  22→2,  11→1,  90→0\n\nCount array (digit → count):\n  digit 0: count=1  (90)\n  digit 1: count=1  (11)\n  digit 2: count=2  (12, 22)\n  digit 3: count=0\n  digit 4: count=2  (64, 34)\n  digit 5: count=1  (25)\n  digit 6-9: count=0\n\nCumulative count:\n  [1, 2, 4, 4, 6, 7, 7, 7, 7, 7]\n   ↑  ↑  ↑     ↑  ↑\n   0≤  ≤1 ≤2   ≤4 ≤5\n\nBuild output (right-to-left):\n  num=90  → digit=0, count[0]=1, output[0]=90,  count[0]=0\n  num=11  → digit=1, count[1]=2, output[1]=11,  count[1]=1\n  num=22  → digit=2, count[2]=4, output[3]=22,  count[2]=3\n  num=12  → digit=2, count[2]=3, output[2]=12,  count[2]=2\n  num=25  → digit=5, count[5]=7, output[6]=25,  count[5]=6\n  num=34  → digit=4, count[4]=6, output[5]=34,  count[4]=5\n  num=64  → digit=4, count[4]=5, output[4]=64,  count[4]=4\n\nAfter Pass 1: [90, 11, 12, 22, 64, 34, 25]\n               ↑   ↑   ↑↑  ↑↑   ↑   ↑\n              (0) (1) (2s)(4s) (5)\n  Note: 12 before 22 (stable ✓), 64 before 34 (stable ✓)\n\n══════════════════════════════════════════\nPASS 2 (exp=10): Sort by TENS digit\n══════════════════════════════════════════\n\nCurrent array: [90, 11, 12, 22, 64, 34, 25]\n\nExtract tens digits:\n  90→9,  11→1,  12→1,  22→2,  64→6,  34→3,  25→2\n\nCount array:\n  digit 1: count=2  (11, 12)\n  digit 2: count=2  (22, 25)\n  digit 3: count=1  (34)\n  digit 6: count=1  (64)\n  digit 9: count=1  (90)\n\nCumulative count:\n  [0, 2, 4, 5, 5, 5, 6, 6, 6, 7]\n      ↑  ↑  ↑        ↑        ↑\n     ≤1 ≤2 ≤3       ≤6       ≤9\n\nBuild output (right-to-left):\n  num=25 → digit=2, count[2]=4, output[3]=25, count[2]=3\n  num=34 → digit=3, count[3]=5, output[4]=34, count[3]=4\n  num=64 → digit=6, count[6]=6, output[5]=64, count[6]=5\n  num=22 → digit=2, count[2]=3, output[2]=22, count[2]=2\n  num=12 → digit=1, count[1]=2, output[1]=12, count[1]=1\n  num=11 → digit=1, count[1]=1, output[0]=11, count[1]=0\n  num=90 → digit=9, count[9]=7, output[6]=90, count[9]=6\n\nAfter Pass 2: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]\n  Note: 11 before 12 — stable from pass 1 ✓ (both had tens digit 1,\n        and 11 came before 12 in current array going right-to-left)\n\nmax_val // 100 = 0 → stop\n\nFinal: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90] ✓\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. Comparison Summary\n\n### Complexity at a Glance\n\n| Algorithm | Best | Average | Worst | Space | Stable? | In-Place? |\n|-----------|------|---------|-------|-------|---------|-----------|\n| Bubble Sort | O(n) | O(n²) | O(n²) | O(1) | Yes | Yes |\n| Selection Sort | O(n²) | O(n²) | O(n²) | O(1) | No* | Yes |\n| Insertion Sort | O(n) | O(n²) | O(n²) | O(1) | Yes | Yes |\n| Merge Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n) | Yes | No |\n| Quick Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n²) | O(log n) | No | Yes |\n| Heap Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(1) | No | Yes |\n| Counting Sort | O(n + k) | O(n + k) | O(n + k) | O(n + k) | Yes | No |\n| Radix Sort | O(d(n+b)) | O(d(n+b)) | O(d(n+b)) | O(n + b) | Yes | No |\n\n*Selection Sort can be made stable with extra bookkeeping, but the classic version isn't.\n\n### When to Use Each\n\n| Scenario | Recommended Algorithm | Why |\n|----------|-----------------------|-----|\n| Small arrays (n < 20) | Insertion Sort | Low overhead, great cache behavior, O(n) best case |\n| Nearly sorted data | Insertion Sort | O(n) adaptive behavior |\n| General purpose, in-place | Quick Sort (randomized) | Best average performance, cache-friendly |\n| Guaranteed O(n log n) | Merge Sort or Heap Sort | No worst-case O(n²) risk |\n| Stable sort required, large data | Merge Sort | Guaranteed O(n log n), stable |\n| Memory is critical | Heap Sort | O(1) space, O(n log n) guaranteed |\n| Integer keys, small range | Counting Sort | O(n + k), beats comparison sorts |\n| Large integers, many elements | Radix Sort | O(d × n), very fast for fixed-width integers |\n| Unknown input, production use | TimSort (Python default) | Hybrid Merge+Insertion; adaptive, stable, O(n log n) |\n\n### Stability Explained\n\nA sort is **stable** if elements with equal keys appear in the same relative order in the output as in the input. This matters when sorting objects by one field when they may already be sorted by another.\n\n```\nInput (sort by first element):  [(3,a), (1,b), (1,c), (2,d)]\nStable output:   [(1,b), (1,c), (2,d), (3,a)]  ← b before c preserved ✓\nUnstable output: [(1,c), (1,b), (2,d), (3,a)]  ← relative order of 1s broken ✗\n```\n\n### The Comparison Lower Bound\n\nAny algorithm that sorts purely by comparing elements requires at least **Ω(n log n)** comparisons in the worst case. This is because sorting n elements is equivalent to identifying which of the n! possible orderings the input represents — and a decision tree of comparisons must have at least n! leaves, requiring height at least log₂(n!) ≈ n log n (by Stirling's approximation).\n\nCounting Sort and Radix Sort **break this bound** because they don't compare elements against each other — they exploit the integer structure of keys. This is why they can achieve O(n) but are restricted to integer-valued (or otherwise bounded, enumerable) keys.","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"b998d7ef-c918-4391-ae46-55d93fa6e617","total_cost_usd":0.26021789999999995,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":15413,"output_tokens":17039,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-sonnet-4-6":{"inputTokens":3,"outputTokens":17039,"cacheReadInputTokens":15413,"cacheCreationInputTokens":0,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.26021789999999995,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"3316d3e8-b7d7-45c0-b70a-62a00a709613"}
